{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775841371304,"sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","part":{"id":"prt_d7864e11a001DMzVtYvEAOpHRj","messageID":"msg_d7864ceb9001Nf0A6D6FojbaMP","sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_4b6c83580f6f4b2a88558e3c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/pkg/picod/config.go"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/pkg/picod/config.go</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: package picod\n2: \n3: import (\n4: \t\"flag\"\n5: )\n6: \n7: type Config struct {\n8: \tPort      int    `json:\"port\"`\n9: \tWorkspace string `json:\"workspace\"`\n10: }\n11: \n12: func ParseFlags() Config {\n13: \tport := flag.Int(\"port\", 8080, \"Port for the PicoD server to listen on\")\n14: \tworkspace := flag.String(\"workspace\", \"\", \"Root directory for file operations (default: current working directory)\")\n15: \tflag.Parse()\n16: \treturn Config{\n17: \t\tPort:      *port,\n18: \t\tWorkspace: *workspace,\n19: \t}\n20: }\n\n(End of file - total 20 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"package picod\n\nimport (\n\t\"flag\"\n)\n\ntype Config struct {\n\tPort      int    `json:\"port\"`\n\tWorkspace string `json:\"workspace\"`\n}\n\nfunc ParseFlags() Config {\n\tport := flag.Int(\"port\", 8080, \"Port for the PicoD server to listen on\")\n\tworkspace := flag.String(\"workspace\", \"\", \"Root directory for file operations (default: current working directory)\")\n\tflag.Parse()\n\treturn Config{\n\t\tPort:      *port,\n\t\tWorkspace: *workspace,\n\t}\n}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/pkg/picod/config.go","time":{"start":1775841371295,"end":1775841371302}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775841371949,"sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","part":{"id":"prt_d7864e52d001T0K2u0aGVarkGC","messageID":"msg_d7864ceb9001Nf0A6D6FojbaMP","sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_96807d02c0ee4de7b0ab6bd6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/specs/code-execution/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/specs/code-execution/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Code Execution (PicoD) Specification\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail, manages workspace files, and exposes a health endpoint with JWT (RSA)ŌĆōprotected APIs.\n6: \n7: ## Requirements\n8: \n9: ### Requirement: Command execution API\n10: \n11: The system SHALL accept `POST /api/execute` with a JSON body, run `command[0]` with `command[1:]` as arguments via `exec.CommandContext`, capture stdout and stderr into buffers, and respond with HTTP 200 and an `ExecuteResponse` for successful request handling (including non-zero command exit). The request SHALL NOT accept stdin from the client; the process stdin is not set from the request body.\n12: \n13: #### Scenario: Valid execution with defaults\n14: \n15: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body with non-empty `command` and empty `timeout`\n16: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n17: - **THEN** the server uses a default timeout of 60 seconds, runs the command, and returns `stdout`, `stderr`, `exit_code`, `duration` (seconds), `start_time`, and `end_time` as JSON\n18: \n19: #### Scenario: Custom timeout\n20: \n21: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body where `timeout` is a non-empty string parseable by Go `time.ParseDuration` (e.g. `\"30s\"`, `\"500ms\"`)\n22: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n23: - **THEN** the server uses that duration for the command context timeout\n24: \n25: #### Scenario: Timeout exceeded\n26: \n27: - **GIVEN** execution exceeds the context deadline\n28: - **WHEN** the context is cancelled\n29: - **THEN** the response `exit_code` SHALL be `124` (`TimeoutExitCode`) and stderr SHALL include a message that the command timed out with the timeout length in seconds (integer formatting)\n30: \n31: #### Scenario: Invalid timeout\n32: \n33: - **GIVEN** `timeout` is non-empty and not a valid duration\n34: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n35: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON `error` describing invalid timeout format and `code` 400\n36: \n37: #### Scenario: Empty command\n38: \n39: - **GIVEN** JSON binds successfully but `command` has length zero\n40: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n41: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` `\"command cannot be empty\"` and `code` 400\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Working directory inside workspace\n44: \n45: - **GIVEN** `working_dir` is non-empty\n46: - **WHEN** the server resolves it with the same path-safety rules as file APIs\n47: - **THEN** `cmd.Dir` is set to the sanitized absolute path; if resolution fails, the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` prefixed by `\"Invalid working directory: \"`\n48: \n49: #### Scenario: Environment augmentation\n50: \n51: - **GIVEN** `env` is non-empty\n52: - **WHEN** the command runs\n53: - **THEN** `cmd.Env` is the current process environment plus additional entries `key=value` for each map entry\n54: \n55: #### Scenario: Malformed JSON\n56: \n57: - **GIVEN** the body is not valid JSON for `ExecuteRequest`\n58: - **WHEN** binding fails\n59: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` from the binder and `code` 400\n60: \n61: ### Requirement: File upload API\n62: \n63: The system SHALL accept `POST /api/files`. If `Content-Type` starts with `multipart/form-data`, the server SHALL treat the request as multipart upload; otherwise it SHALL bind JSON for `UploadFileRequest`.\n64: \n65: #### Scenario: Multipart upload\n66: \n67: - **GIVEN** `Content-Type` has prefix `multipart/form-data`, form field `path` is set, and form file `file` is present\n68: - **WHEN** the client posts to `POST /api/files`\n69: - **THEN** the server creates parent directories with mode `0755`, writes the uploaded stream to a sanitized path, applies mode from form field `mode` via `parseFileMode` (default `0644` when empty/invalid/exceeds max), and responds HTTP 200 with `FileInfo` using `path` as relative to the workspace root\n70: \n71: #### Scenario: Multipart missing path or file\n72: \n73: - **GIVEN** multipart request with empty `path` or missing/unreadable `file`\n74: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n75: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with an appropriate `error` and `code` 400\n76: \n77: #### Scenario: JSON Base64 upload\n78: \n79: - **GIVEN** non-multipart request with JSON `path` and `content` (Base64 standard encoding) required\n80: - **WHEN** the client posts to `POST /api/files`\n81: - **THEN** the server decodes content, creates directories, writes the file with `parseFileMode` on `mode`, and responds HTTP 200 with `FileInfo` (relative `path`)\n82: \n83: #### Scenario: Invalid Base64\n84: \n85: - **GIVEN** JSON upload with invalid Base64 in `content`\n86: - **WHEN** decoding fails\n87: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` describing invalid base64 and `code` 400\n88: \n89: ### Requirement: File listing API\n90: \n91: The system SHALL accept `GET /api/files?path=...`, require the `path` query parameter, read the directory at the sanitized path, and return JSON `ListFilesResponse`.\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: Successful listing\n94: \n95: - **GIVEN** `path` refers to an existing directory inside the workspace\n96: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files?path=<dir>`\n97: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 200 with `files` as an array of `FileEntry` objects (`name`, `size`, `modified`, `mode`, `is_dir`), skipping entries where `entry.Info()` fails\n98: \n99: #### Scenario: Missing query parameter\n100: \n101: - **GIVEN** the `path` query parameter is absent or empty\n102: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files`\n103: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` `\"Missing 'path' query parameter\"` and `code` 400\n104: \n105: #### Scenario: Directory not found\n106: \n107: - **GIVEN** sanitized path does not exist\n108: - **WHEN** `os.ReadDir` fails with not exist\n109: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `error` `\"Directory not found\"` and `code` 404\n110: \n111: ### Requirement: File download API\n112: \n113: The system SHALL serve file contents at `GET /api/files/*path` for a sanitized file path, set download-oriented headers, and stream the file with `c.File`.\n114: \n115: #### Scenario: Successful download\n116: \n117: - **GIVEN** the wildcard path resolves to a regular file inside the workspace\n118: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/<path>`\n119: - **THEN** the server sets `Content-Description` to `File Transfer`, `Content-Transfer-Encoding` to `binary`, `Content-Disposition` to `attachment; filename=\"<basename>\"`, `Content-Type` from `mime.TypeByExtension` or `application/octet-stream`, and returns the file body\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: Path escapes workspace\n122: \n123: - **GIVEN** the requested path fails `sanitizePath`\n124: - **WHEN** the client calls the download endpoint\n125: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` describing access denied / workspace jail\n126: \n127: #### Scenario: Not a file\n128: \n129: - **GIVEN** the path exists but is a directory\n130: - **WHEN** the client downloads\n131: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` `\"Path is a directory, not a file\"` and `code` 400\n132: \n133: #### Scenario: File missing\n134: \n135: - **GIVEN** the path does not exist\n136: - **WHEN** stat fails with not exist\n137: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `error` `\"File not found\"` and `code` 404\n138: \n139: ### Requirement: Health endpoint\n140: \n141: The system SHALL expose `GET /health` without JWT middleware and respond HTTP 200 with JSON including `status`, `service`, `version`, and `uptime`.\n142: \n143: #### Scenario: Unauthenticated health\n144: \n145: - **GIVEN** no `Authorization` header\n146: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /health`\n147: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 200 with `status` `\"ok\"`, `service` `\"PicoD\"`, `version` `\"0.0.1\"`, and `uptime` as a string from `time.Since(server start)`\n148: \n149: ### Requirement: JWT authentication for API routes\n150: \n151: The system SHALL register `/api` routes under a Gin group that uses `AuthManager.AuthMiddleware`. The middleware SHALL require header `Authorization: Bearer <token>`, parse the JWT with an RSA public key, and reject non-RSA signing methods. Valid tokens SHALL allow the request to proceed; after validation the request body SHALL be wrapped with `http.MaxBytesReader` limiting size to `MaxBodySize`.\n152: \n153: #### Scenario: Missing or malformed Authorization\n154: \n155: - **GIVEN** missing header, or a header that is not exactly two space-separated parts with first part `Bearer`\n156: - **WHEN** an `/api` route is hit\n157: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with JSON including `error`, `code` 401, and `detail` explaining the failure\n158: \n159: #### Scenario: Invalid or expired JWT\n160: \n161: - **GIVEN** a Bearer token that fails verification (signature, expiry, etc.) with options `WithExpirationRequired`, `WithIssuedAt`, and `WithLeeway(1 minute)`\n162: - **WHEN** the middleware runs\n163: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with `error` `\"Invalid token\"`, `code` 401, and `detail` containing the verification error\n164: \n165: #### Scenario: Public key required at startup\n166: \n167: - **GIVEN** `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` is unset or does not decode to an RSA public key in PEM form\n168: - **WHEN** `NewServer` initializes\n169: - **THEN** the process SHALL log a fatal error and not continue serving (there is no unauthenticated API mode when the key is missing)\n170: \n171: ### Requirement: Server configuration\n172: \n173: The system SHALL read CLI flags `-port` and `-workspace`, build `picod.Config`, and listen on `\":<port>\"`. If `workspace` is empty, the workspace root SHALL be the current working directory (fatal if `os.Getwd` fails). The HTTP server SHALL use `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds.\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: Defaults from CLI\n176: \n177: - **GIVEN** `-port` and `-workspace` use program defaults\n178: - **WHEN** the binary starts\n179: - **THEN** `port` defaults to `8080`, `workspace` defaults to empty (resolved to CWD), and Gin runs in `ReleaseMode` with `Logger` and `Recovery` middleware globally\n\n(End of file - total 179 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Code Execution (PicoD) Specification\n\n## Purpose\n\nPicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail, manages workspace files, and exposes a health endpoint with JWT (RSA)ŌĆōprotected APIs.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Command execution API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/execute` with a JSON body, run `command[0]` with `command[1:]` as arguments via `exec.CommandContext`, capture stdout and stderr into buffers, and respond with HTTP 200 and an `ExecuteResponse` for successful request handling (including non-zero command exit). The request SHALL NOT accept stdin from the client; the process stdin is not set from the request body.\n\n#### Scenario: Valid execution with defaults\n\n- **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body with non-empty `command` and empty `timeout`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n- **THEN** the server uses a default timeout of 60 seconds, runs the command, and returns `stdout`, `stderr`, `exit_code`, `duration` (seconds), `start_time`, and `end_time` as JSON\n\n#### Scenario: Custom timeout\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"specs/code-execution/spec.md","time":{"start":1775841371942,"end":1775841371947}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775841372030,"sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","part":{"id":"prt_d7864e771001vWXX11BheMwzU7","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d7864ceb9001Nf0A6D6FojbaMP","sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":41430,"input":41290,"output":110,"reasoning":30,"cache":{"write":0,"read":0}},"cost":0.01162718}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775841373675,"sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","part":{"id":"prt_d7864ede6001eFNrO0PHFZSH9O","messageID":"msg_d7864e797001kvTYEGDYRcjCd5","sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1775841550304,"sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","part":{"id":"prt_d786504c0001D4kCziHUFhOiF6","messageID":"msg_d7864e797001kvTYEGDYRcjCd5","sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","type":"text","text":"Now I have all the context needed. Let me write the delta-spec.md for AR-016.","time":{"start":1775841550302,"end":1775841550302}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775841550314,"sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","part":{"id":"prt_d786506b4001Bq1uyqaQJyCqpx","messageID":"msg_d7864e797001kvTYEGDYRcjCd5","sessionID":"ses_2879dcf1effe8NzjFZahhxooEQ","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_64d3778fc1b844528806c3ce","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# AR-016: PicoD µ¢ćõ╗Čń«ĪńÉå API ŌĆö Delta Spec\n\n## Context\n\n- **Module:** `pkg/picod`\n- **Language:** Go\n- **Size:** M\n- **Base specs:** `code-execution/spec.md`, `delta-spec.md` (AR-015), `deployment/client-go.md`\n\n## Delta Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Route table reorganization\n\nThe system SHALL reorganize file management routes under explicit sub-paths. The following routes SHALL exist under the `/api` group with JWT auth middleware:\n\n| Method | Path | Handler |\n|--------|------|---------|\n| POST | `/api/files/read` | ReadFileHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/write` | WriteFileHandler |\n| GET | `/api/files/stat` | StatFileHandler |\n| GET | `/api/files` | ListFilesHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/upload` | UploadFileHandler |\n| GET | `/api/files/download` | DownloadFileHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/delete` | DeleteFileHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/move` | MoveFileHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/mkdir` | MkDirHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/search` | SearchFilesHandler |\n| POST | `/api/files/chmod` | ChmodHandler |\n\nThe legacy routes `POST /api/files` (upload), `GET /api/files` (list), and `GET /api/files/*path` (download) from AR-015 SHALL be replaced. `GET /api/files` SHALL serve dual purpose: with `path` query parameter it lists directory contents; without `path` it returns HTTP 400.\n\n#### Scenario: All new routes are registered\n\n- **GIVEN** `NewServer` completes successfully\n- **WHEN** the route table is inspected\n- **THEN** all eleven file management routes exist under `/api/files/*` plus `POST /api/execute` and `GET /health`\n\n#### Scenario: Legacy POST /api/files upload route is removed\n\n- **GIVEN** the AR-016 server is running\n- **WHEN** a client calls `POST /api/files` with multipart content\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 (route no longer exists) or HTTP 400 (no `path` query parameter)\n\n#### Scenario: Legacy GET /api/files/*path download route is removed\n\n- **GIVEN** the AR-016 server is running\n- **WHEN** a client calls `GET /api/files/some/file.txt`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 (wildcard route no longer exists)\n\n#### Scenario: Download uses query parameter\n\n- **GIVEN** a file exists at `workspaceDir/docs/readme.md`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/download?path=docs/readme.md`\n- **THEN** the file is served with appropriate download headers\n\n### Requirement: Config extension for file management\n\nThe `Config` struct SHALL be extended with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Type | Default | Meaning |\n|-------|------|---------|---------|\n| `MaxChunkSize` | `int64` | `32 << 20` (32 MiB) | Maximum size per chunk in chunked transfer |\n| `MaxBatchSize` | `int` | `100` | Maximum number of paths in a single batch operation |\n| `MaxSearchResults` | `int` | `100` | Maximum number of results returned by search |\n| `MaxSearchDepth` | `int` | `50` | Maximum directory depth for glob search |\n\nThe CLI flag parser SHALL accept `--max-chunk-size`, `--max-batch-size`, `--max-search-results`, and `--max-search-depth`.\n\n#### Scenario: Default config values\n\n- **GIVEN** no file management flags are provided\n- **WHEN** `ParseFlags` returns\n- **THEN** `MaxChunkSize` is `33554432`, `MaxBatchSize` is `100`, `MaxSearchResults` is `100`, `MaxSearchDepth` is `50`\n\n#### Scenario: Custom config values\n\n- **GIVEN** `--max-chunk-size=16777216 --max-batch-size=50 --max-search-results=200 --max-search-depth=20`\n- **WHEN** `ParseFlags` returns\n- **THEN** the config fields reflect the provided values\n\n### Requirement: ReadFile API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/read` with JSON body binding to `ReadFileRequest`. The handler SHALL read file content from the sanitized path, encode as Base64, and return `ReadFileResponse`.\n\n```\nReadFileRequest:\n  path:   string (required)\n  offset: int64  (optional, default: 0)\n  limit:  int64  (optional, default: -1 meaning read to EOF)\n\nReadFileResponse:\n  content:    string (Base64 encoded)\n  total_size: int64  (full file size)\n  read_bytes: int64  (actual bytes read)\n```\n\nThe handler SHALL open the file, seek to `offset`, read up to `limit` bytes (or to EOF if `limit < 0`), and Base64-encode the result. If `offset` exceeds file size, `content` SHALL be empty and `read_bytes` SHALL be `0`.\n\n#### Scenario: Read entire file\n\n- **GIVEN** a file `workspaceDir/hello.txt` containing `\"Hello, World!\"` (13 bytes)\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/read` with `{\"path\": \"hello.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with `{\"content\": \"<base64 of 'Hello, World!'>\", \"total_size\": 13, \"read_bytes\": 13}`\n\n#### Scenario: Read with offset\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"Hello, World!\"`\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"hello.txt\", \"offset\": 7}`\n- **THEN** `content` is Base64 of `\"World!\"`, `total_size` is `13`, `read_bytes` is `6`\n\n#### Scenario: Read with offset and limit\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"Hello, World!\"`\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"hello.txt\", \"offset\": 7, \"limit\": 5}`\n- **THEN** `content` is Base64 of `\"World\"`, `total_size` is `13`, `read_bytes` is `5`\n\n#### Scenario: Offset exceeds file size\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"Hi\"` (2 bytes)\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"hi.txt\", \"offset\": 100}`\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with `{\"content\": \"\", \"total_size\": 2, \"read_bytes\": 0}`\n\n#### Scenario: Limit exceeds remaining bytes\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"Hello\"` (5 bytes)\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"hello.txt\", \"offset\": 3, \"limit\": 100}`\n- **THEN** `content` is Base64 of `\"lo\"`, `total_size` is `5`, `read_bytes` is `2`\n\n#### Scenario: Read directory returns error\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` points to a directory\n- **WHEN** the handler attempts to read\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"Path is a directory, not a file\", \"code\": 400}`\n\n#### Scenario: File not found\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` does not exist\n- **WHEN** the handler attempts to open the file\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"File not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n#### Scenario: Path traversal blocked\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` is `\"../../etc/passwd\"`\n- **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with access denied error\n\n#### Scenario: Negative offset treated as zero\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"test\"`\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"test.txt\", \"offset\": -1}`\n- **THEN** the handler treats offset as `0` and reads the entire file\n\n### Requirement: WriteFile API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/write` with JSON body binding to `WriteFileRequest`. The handler SHALL decode Base64 content and write to the sanitized path.\n\n```\nWriteFileRequest:\n  path:          string (required)\n  content:       string (Base64 encoded, required)\n  offset:        int64  (optional, default: 0)\n  mode:          string (optional, \"overwrite\" | \"append\", default: \"overwrite\")\n  create_parent: bool   (optional, default: false)\n```\n\nIn `overwrite` mode with `offset=0`, the file SHALL be truncated and replaced. In `overwrite` mode with `offset>0`, the handler SHALL seek to offset and overwrite bytes in place without truncating beyond the written data. In `append` mode, the content SHALL be appended to the end of the file (offset is ignored). If `create_parent` is true, parent directories SHALL be created with mode `0755`.\n\n```\nWriteFileResponse:\n  path:        string (relative to workspace)\n  size:        int64  (new file size after write)\n  bytes_written: int64\n```\n\n#### Scenario: Overwrite entire file\n\n- **GIVEN** a file `workspaceDir/data.txt` containing `\"old content\"`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/write` with `{\"path\": \"data.txt\", \"content\": \"<base64 of 'new content'>\"}`\n- **THEN** the file contains `\"new content\"`, and the response is HTTP 200 with `{\"path\": \"data.txt\", \"size\": 11, \"bytes_written\": 11}`\n\n#### Scenario: Append to file\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"Hello\"`\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"hello.txt\", \"content\": \"<base64 of ', World!'>\", \"mode\": \"append\"}`\n- **THEN** the file contains `\"Hello, World!\"`, and `bytes_written` is `8`\n\n#### Scenario: Write at offset\n\n- **GIVEN** a file containing `\"Hello, World!\"` (13 bytes)\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"hello.txt\", \"content\": \"<base64 of 'GO'>\", \"offset\": 7}`\n- **THEN** the file contains `\"Hello, GOrld!\"`, and `bytes_written` is `2`\n\n#### Scenario: Create parent directories\n\n- **GIVEN** directory `workspaceDir/a/` exists but `a/b/` does not\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"a/b/c.txt\", \"content\": \"<base64 of 'data'>\", \"create_parent\": true}`\n- **THEN** directories `a/b/` are created with mode `0755`, file `c.txt` is written, and response is HTTP 200\n\n#### Scenario: Create parent disabled fails\n\n- **GIVEN** parent directory does not exist\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"nonexistent/dir/file.txt\", \"content\": \"<base64 of 'data'>\", \"create_parent\": false}`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 or 500 with an error describing the failure to create the file\n\n#### Scenario: Invalid Base64 content\n\n- **GIVEN** `\"content\": \"not-valid-base64!!!\"`\n- **WHEN** `base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString` is called\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON error describing invalid base64\n\n#### Scenario: Write to directory returns error\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` points to a directory\n- **WHEN** the handler attempts to write\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error indicating path is a directory\n\n### Requirement: StatFile API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `GET /api/files/stat?path=...` and return metadata about the file or directory at the sanitized path.\n\n```\nStatFileResponse:\n  name:       string\n  size:       int64\n  mode:       string (octal permission string, e.g. \"0755\")\n  mod_time:   time.Time\n  is_dir:     bool\n  is_symlink: bool\n```\n\nThe `is_symlink` field SHALL be `true` if the path itself is a symbolic link (checked via `os.Lstat`).\n\n#### Scenario: Stat a regular file\n\n- **GIVEN** a file `workspaceDir/test.txt` with size 100 bytes, mode `0644`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/stat?path=test.txt`\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with `{\"name\": \"test.txt\", \"size\": 100, \"mode\": \"0644\", \"mod_time\": \"...\", \"is_dir\": false, \"is_symlink\": false}`\n\n#### Scenario: Stat a directory\n\n- **GIVEN** directory `workspaceDir/src/` exists\n- **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/stat?path=src`\n- **THEN** the response has `is_dir: true`\n\n#### Scenario: Stat a symlink\n\n- **GIVEN** a symlink `workspaceDir/link` pointing to `test.txt`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/stat?path=link`\n- **THEN** the response has `is_symlink: true`\n\n#### Scenario: Path not found\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` does not exist\n- **WHEN** `os.Lstat` returns `os.IsNotExist`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"File not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n#### Scenario: Path traversal blocked\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` is `\"../../../etc/shadow\"`\n- **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with access denied error\n\n### Requirement: DeleteFile API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/delete` with JSON body containing `path` (string) or `paths` ([]string). A single `path` SHALL delete one file or empty directory. `paths` SHALL perform batch deletion of up to `MaxBatchSize` entries.\n\n```\nDeleteFileRequest:\n  path:  string   (optional, single path)\n  paths: []string (optional, batch paths)\n```\n\nBatch deletion SHALL use transactional semantics: if any single deletion fails, the handler SHALL continue with remaining paths and report partial results. The response SHALL indicate which paths succeeded and which failed.\n\n```\nDeleteFileResponse:\n  deleted: []string (successfully deleted paths)\n  failed:  []DeleteFailure (paths that failed)\n\nDeleteFailure:\n  path:  string\n  error: string\n```\n\nDirectories SHALL only be deleted if empty (use `os.Remove`, not `os.RemoveAll`). Non-empty directories SHALL return an error in `failed`.\n\n#### Scenario: Delete a single file\n\n- **GIVEN** file `workspaceDir/tmp.txt` exists\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/delete` with `{\"path\": \"tmp.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the file is removed and response is HTTP 200 with `{\"deleted\": [\"tmp.txt\"], \"failed\": []}`\n\n#### Scenario: Delete non-existent file\n\n- **GIVEN** file `workspaceDir/ghost.txt` does not exist\n- **WHEN** the client calls `{\"path\": \"ghost.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"File not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n#### Scenario: Batch delete all succeed\n\n- **GIVEN** files `a.txt`, `b.txt`, `c.txt` exist\n- **WHEN** the client calls `{\"paths\": [\"a.txt\", \"b.txt\", \"c.txt\"]}`\n- **THEN** all three files are deleted and `deleted` contains all three paths\n\n#### Scenario: Batch delete partial failure\n\n- **GIVEN** files `a.txt`, `c.txt` exist but `b.txt` does not\n- **WHEN** the client calls `{\"paths\": [\"a.txt\", \"b.txt\", \"c.txt\"]}`\n- **THEN** `a.txt` and `c.txt` are deleted, `deleted` contains `[\"a.txt\", \"c.txt\"]`, and `failed` contains `{\"path\": \"b.txt\", \"error\": \"File not found\"}`\n\n#### Scenario: Batch delete exceeds MaxBatchSize\n\n- **GIVEN** `MaxBatchSize` is `100` and client sends `101` paths\n- **WHEN** the handler validates the request\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"Batch size exceeds maximum of 100\", \"code\": 400}`\n\n#### Scenario: Delete non-empty directory fails\n\n- **GIVEN** directory `workspaceDir/logs/` contains files\n- **WHEN** the client calls `{\"path\": \"logs\"}`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error indicating directory is not empty\n\n#### Scenario: Delete empty directory succeeds\n\n- **GIVEN** empty directory `workspaceDir/empty/` exists\n- **WHEN** the client calls `{\"path\": \"empty\"}`\n- **THEN** the directory is removed and response indicates success\n\n### Requirement: MoveFile API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/move` with JSON body to rename or move a file or directory.\n\n```\nMoveFileRequest:\n  source:      string (required)\n  destination: string (required)\n```\n\nThe handler SHALL use `os.Rename` for the operation. If the destination's parent directory does not exist, the handler SHALL return an error (no automatic parent creation).\n\n```\nMoveFileResponse:\n  source:      string\n  destination: string\n```\n\n#### Scenario: Move file within workspace\n\n- **GIVEN** file `workspaceDir/old.txt` exists\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/move` with `{\"source\": \"old.txt\", \"destination\": \"new.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the file is renamed and response is HTTP 200 with `{\"source\": \"old.txt\", \"destination\": \"new.txt\"}`\n\n#### Scenario: Move to subdirectory\n\n- **GIVEN** file `workspaceDir/a.txt` exists and directory `workspaceDir/sub/` exists\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"source\": \"a.txt\", \"destination\": \"sub/a.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the file is moved to `sub/a.txt`\n\n#### Scenario: Source does not exist\n\n- **GIVEN** `source` path does not exist\n- **WHEN** the handler calls `os.Rename`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"Source file not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n#### Scenario: Destination parent does not exist\n\n- **GIVEN** directory `workspaceDir/nonexistent/` does not exist\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"source\": \"a.txt\", \"destination\": \"nonexistent/a.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error describing the failure\n\n#### Scenario: Move escapes workspace\n\n- **GIVEN** `destination` is `\"../../etc/hostname\"`\n- **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called on destination\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with access denied error\n\n### Requirement: MkDir API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/mkdir` with JSON body to create a directory (recursively).\n\n```\nMkDirRequest:\n  path: string (required)\n  mode: string (optional, octal string, default: \"0755\")\n```\n\nThe handler SHALL use `os.MkdirAll` to create the directory and all parent directories.\n\n```\nMkDirResponse:\n  path: string (relative to workspace)\n  created: bool (true if created, false if already existed)\n```\n\n#### Scenario: Create new directory\n\n- **GIVEN** directory `workspaceDir/a/b/` does not exist\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/mkdir` with `{\"path\": \"a/b\"}`\n- **THEN** directories `a/` and `a/b/` are created with mode `0755` and response has `created: true`\n\n#### Scenario: Directory already exists\n\n- **GIVEN** directory `workspaceDir/existing/` exists\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"existing\"}`\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with `created: false` and no error\n\n#### Scenario: Create with custom mode\n\n- **GIVEN** directory does not exist\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"secret\", \"mode\": \"0700\"}`\n- **THEN** the directory is created with mode `0700`\n\n#### Scenario: Path is an existing file\n\n- **GIVEN** `workspaceDir/file.txt` is a regular file\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"file.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error indicating path already exists as a file\n\n### Requirement: SearchFiles API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/search` with JSON body to search for files matching a glob pattern within a directory tree.\n\n```\nSearchFilesRequest:\n  path:        string (required, search root directory)\n  pattern:     string (required, glob pattern)\n  max_results: int    (optional, default: from config MaxSearchResults)\n```\n\nThe handler SHALL use `filepath.WalkDir` to traverse the directory tree rooted at `path`, matching entry names against `pattern` using `path.Match`. Traversal SHALL respect `MaxSearchDepth` (default 50) to limit directory depth. Results SHALL be limited to `max_results` entries.\n\n```\nSearchFilesResponse:\n  matches:   []FileInfo\n  truncated: bool (true if results were limited by max_results)\n```\n\n`FileInfo` in search results SHALL include the relative path from the workspace root.\n\n#### Scenario: Find matching files\n\n- **GIVEN** workspace contains `src/main.go`, `src/util.go`, `src/test/main_test.go`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/search` with `{\"path\": \"src\", \"pattern\": \"*.go\"}`\n- **THEN** the response contains `matches` for `src/main.go` and `src/util.go` (not `main_test.go`)\n\n#### Scenario: Recursive glob pattern\n\n- **GIVEN** workspace contains `a/1.txt`, `a/b/2.txt`, `a/b/c/3.txt`\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `{\"path\": \"a\", \"pattern\": \"*.txt\"}`\n- **THEN** all three `.txt` files are returned\n\n#### Scenario: Results truncated\n\n- **GIVEN** `MaxSearchResults` is `2` and 5 files match the pattern\n- **WHEN** the handler runs\n- **THEN** `matches` contains 2 entries and `truncated` is `true`\n\n#### Scenario: No matches\n\n- **GIVEN** no files match the pattern\n- **WHEN** the handler runs\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with `{\"matches\": [], \"truncated\": false}`\n\n#### Scenario: Search root does not exist\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` does not exist\n- **WHEN** the handler checks the search root\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"Directory not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n#### Scenario: Search root is a file\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` points to a regular file\n- **WHEN** the handler checks the search root\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error indicating path is not a directory\n\n#### Scenario: Invalid glob pattern\n\n- **GIVEN** `pattern` is an invalid glob (e.g. `\"*[`)\n- **WHEN** `path.Match` is called\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error describing the invalid pattern\n\n#### Scenario: Depth limit respected\n\n- **GIVEN** a directory tree 60 levels deep and `MaxSearchDepth` is `50`\n- **WHEN** the handler walks the tree\n- **THEN** directories beyond depth 50 are not traversed\n\n### Requirement: Chmod API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/files/chmod` with JSON body to change file or directory permissions.\n\n```\nChmodRequest:\n  path: string (required)\n  mode: string (required, octal string, e.g. \"0755\")\n```\n\nThe handler SHALL parse the octal mode string and call `os.Chmod` on the sanitized path.\n\n```\nChmodResponse:\n  path: string\n  mode: string (the applied mode as octal string)\n```\n\n#### Scenario: Change file permissions\n\n- **GIVEN** file `workspaceDir/script.sh` with mode `0644`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/files/chmod` with `{\"path\": \"script.sh\", \"mode\": \"0755\"}`\n- **THEN** the file mode is changed to `0755` and response is HTTP 200 with `{\"path\": \"script.sh\", \"mode\": \"0755\"}`\n\n#### Scenario: Invalid mode format\n\n- **GIVEN** `mode` is `\"abc\"`\n- **WHEN** the handler parses the mode\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error describing invalid mode format\n\n#### Scenario: Mode exceeds max\n\n- **GIVEN** `mode` is `\"07777\"` (exceeds `0777`)\n- **WHEN** the handler validates the mode\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with error indicating mode is out of range\n\n#### Scenario: Path does not exist\n\n- **GIVEN** `path` does not exist\n- **WHEN** `os.Chmod` is called\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"File not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n### Requirement: Chunked upload support\n\nUploadFileHandler SHALL support chunked transfer via HTTP headers `X-Chunk-Index` (0-based) and `X-Chunk-Total` (total number of chunks). When chunk headers are present, the handler SHALL write each chunk to a temporary file and merge on the final chunk.\n\nFor multipart chunked upload:\n- Each chunk SHALL include form field `chunk_index` and `chunk_total` in addition to `path` and `file`\n- Chunks SHALL be written to a temporary file named `<path>.chunk.<index>` in a temp directory\n- When `chunk_index == chunk_total - 1`, all chunks SHALL be concatenated in order and written to the final path\n- Temporary chunk files SHALL be cleaned up after merge or on error\n\nFor JSON Base64 chunked upload:\n- Each request SHALL include `chunk_index` and `chunk_total` fields in the JSON body\n- Same temp file and merge behavior as multipart\n\n#### Scenario: Single chunk upload (no chunk headers)\n\n- **GIVEN** no `X-Chunk-Index` or `X-Chunk-Total` headers\n- **WHEN** the upload handler runs\n- **THEN** the file is written directly (existing behavior, no temp files)\n\n#### Scenario: Multi-chunk upload completes\n\n- **GIVEN** a file split into 3 chunks\n- **WHEN** the client sends chunk 0, then chunk 1, then chunk 2 (with `X-Chunk-Total: 3`)\n- **THEN** after chunk 2, the final file contains the concatenated content of all 3 chunks in order\n\n#### Scenario: Chunk out of order\n\n- **GIVEN** chunks arrive in order 2, 0, 1\n- **WHEN** all 3 chunks are received\n- **THEN** the final file is correctly assembled in order 0, 1, 2\n\n#### Scenario: Chunk exceeds MaxChunkSize\n\n- **GIVEN** `MaxChunkSize` is `1048576` (1 MiB) and a chunk body is `2097152` bytes\n- **WHEN** the handler checks the chunk size\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 413 with `{\"error\": \"Chunk size exceeds maximum\", \"code\": 413}`\n\n#### Scenario: Temp files cleaned up after merge\n\n- **GIVEN** a 3-chunk upload completes successfully\n- **WHEN** the temp directory is inspected\n- **THEN** no `.chunk.*` files remain\n\n### Requirement: Chunked download support\n\nDownloadFileHandler SHALL support HTTP `Range` requests for partial file downloads. When a `Range` header is present (format: `bytes=start-end`), the handler SHALL respond with HTTP 206 Partial Content and the requested byte range.\n\n#### Scenario: Full download without Range header\n\n- **GIVEN** a file of 1000 bytes\n- **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/download?path=file.bin` without `Range` header\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with the full 1000 bytes and `Content-Length: 1000`\n\n#### Scenario: Partial download with Range header\n\n- **GIVEN** a file of 1000 bytes\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `Range: bytes=0-499`\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 206 with `Content-Range: bytes 0-499/1000`, `Content-Length: 500`, and the first 500 bytes\n\n#### Scenario: Range from offset to end\n\n- **GIVEN** a file of 1000 bytes\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `Range: bytes=500-`\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 206 with bytes 500-999 (500 bytes)\n\n#### Scenario: Range beyond file size\n\n- **GIVEN** a file of 100 bytes\n- **WHEN** the client calls with `Range: bytes=200-300`\n- **THEN** the server responds HTTP 416 with `{\"error\": \"Range not satisfiable\", \"code\": 416}`\n\n### Requirement: files/ subpackage structure\n\nThe system SHALL refactor file management logic from `pkg/picod/files.go` into `pkg/picod/files/` subpackage. The subpackage SHALL export a `FileManager` interface and individual handler constructors.\n\n```\npkg/picod/files/\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ manager.go      ŌĆö FileManager interface + implementation\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ read.go         ŌĆö ReadFileHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ write.go        ŌĆö WriteFileHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ stat.go         ŌĆö StatFileHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ list.go         ŌĆö ListFilesHandler (migrated from AR-015)\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ upload.go       ŌĆö UploadFileHandler (migrated from AR-015, with chunk support)\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ download.go     ŌĆö DownloadFileHandler (migrated from AR-015, with Range support)\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ delete.go       ŌĆö DeleteFileHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ move.go         ŌĆö MoveFileHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ mkdir.go        ŌĆö MkDirHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ search.go       ŌĆö SearchFilesHandler\nŌö£ŌöĆŌöĆ chmod.go        ŌĆö ChmodHandler\nŌööŌöĆŌöĆ types.go        ŌĆö Request/Response structs, constants\n```\n\nThe `FileManager` interface SHALL encapsulate all file operations and accept a sanitized workspace root path. Handlers SHALL be methods on a struct that embeds or holds a `FileManager`.\n\n#### Scenario: FileManager interface exists\n\n- **GIVEN** the `pkg/picod/files/` package\n- **WHEN** the package is compiled\n- **THEN** a `FileManager` interface is exported with methods for read, write, stat, list, upload, download, delete, move, mkdir, search, and chmod\n\n#### Scenario: Old files.go is removed\n\n- **GIVEN** AR-016 is complete\n- **WHEN** `pkg/picod/files.go` is inspected\n- **THEN** the file no longer exists (logic migrated to `files/` subpackage)\n\n#### Scenario: Server routes use files/ package handlers\n\n- **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called\n- **WHEN** routes are registered\n- **THEN** file management routes point to handlers from the `files` subpackage\n\n### Requirement: New request/response type definitions\n\nThe system SHALL define the following structs in `pkg/picod/files/types.go` with exact JSON tags:\n\n```go\ntype ReadFileRequest struct {\n    Path   string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Offset int64  `json:\"offset\"`\n    Limit  int64  `json:\"limit\"`\n}\n\ntype ReadFileResponse struct {\n    Content    string `json:\"content\"`\n    TotalSize  int64  `json:\"total_size\"`\n    ReadBytes  int64  `json:\"read_bytes\"`\n}\n\ntype WriteFileRequest struct {\n    Path         string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Content      string `json:\"content\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Offset       int64  `json:\"offset\"`\n    Mode         string `json:\"mode\"`\n    CreateParent bool   `json:\"create_parent\"`\n}\n\ntype WriteFileResponse struct {\n    Path         string `json:\"path\"`\n    Size         int64  `json:\"size\"`\n    BytesWritten int64  `json:\"bytes_written\"`\n}\n\ntype StatFileResponse struct {\n    Name      string    `json:\"name\"`\n    Size      int64     `json:\"size\"`\n    Mode      string    `json:\"mode\"`\n    ModTime   time.Time `json:\"mod_time\"`\n    IsDir     bool      `json:\"is_dir\"`\n    IsSymlink bool      `json:\"is_symlink\"`\n}\n\ntype DeleteFileRequest struct {\n    Path  string   `json:\"path\"`\n    Paths []string `json:\"paths\"`\n}\n\ntype DeleteFileResponse struct {\n    Deleted []string       `json:\"deleted\"`\n    Failed  []DeleteFailure `json:\"failed\"`\n}\n\ntype DeleteFailure struct {\n    Path  string `json:\"path\"`\n    Error string `json:\"error\"`\n}\n\ntype MoveFileRequest struct {\n    Source      string `json:\"source\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Destination string `json:\"destination\" binding:\"required\"`\n}\n\ntype MoveFileResponse struct {\n    Source      string `json:\"source\"`\n    Destination string `json:\"destination\"`\n}\n\ntype MkDirRequest struct {\n    Path string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Mode string `json:\"mode\"`\n}\n\ntype MkDirResponse struct {\n    Path    string `json:\"path\"`\n    Created bool   `json:\"created\"`\n}\n\ntype SearchFilesRequest struct {\n    Path       string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Pattern    string `json:\"pattern\" binding:\"required\"`\n    MaxResults int    `json:\"max_results\"`\n}\n\ntype SearchFilesResponse struct {\n    Matches   []FileEntry `json:\"matches\"`\n    Truncated bool        `json:\"truncated\"`\n}\n\ntype ChmodRequest struct {\n    Path string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n    Mode string `json:\"mode\" binding:\"required\"`\n}\n\ntype ChmodResponse struct {\n    Path string `json:\"path\"`\n    Mode string `json:\"mode\"`\n}\n```\n\n#### Scenario: ReadFileRequest binding\n\n- **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"path\": \"data.bin\", \"offset\": 100, \"limit\": 50}`\n- **WHEN** `ShouldBindJSON` is called\n- **THEN** all fields are populated with correct types\n\n#### Scenario: DeleteFileRequest with single path\n\n- **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"path\": \"tmp.txt\"}`\n- **WHEN** `ShouldBindJSON` is called\n- **THEN** `Path` is `\"tmp.txt\"` and `Paths` is nil/empty\n\n#### Scenario: DeleteFileRequest with batch paths\n\n- **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"paths\": [\"a.txt\", \"b.txt\"]}`\n- **WHEN** `ShouldBindJSON` is called\n- **THEN** `Paths` contains two elements and `Path` is empty\n\n#### Scenario: SearchFilesRequest defaults\n\n- **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"path\": \"src\", \"pattern\": \"*.go\"}` without `max_results`\n- **WHEN** `ShouldBindJSON` is called\n- **THEN** `MaxResults` is `0` (handler shall apply config default)\n\n### Requirement: Error response consistency\n\nAll file management endpoints SHALL use a consistent error response format matching AR-015:\n\n```json\n{\"error\": \"<human-readable message>\", \"code\": <http_status_code>}\n```\n\nThe following HTTP status codes SHALL be used:\n\n| Code | Condition |\n|------|-----------|\n| 400 | Invalid request (bad path, bad format, missing required field, path traversal) |\n| 404 | File or directory not found |\n| 409 | Conflict (e.g., destination exists during move) |\n| 413 | Request body or chunk too large |\n| 416 | Range not satisfiable |\n| 500 | Internal server error (file system operation failure) |\n\n#### Scenario: Consistent 400 response for path traversal\n\n- **GIVEN** any file management endpoint\n- **WHEN** a path traversal attempt is detected\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"Invalid path: access denied: workspace jail violation\", \"code\": 400}`\n\n#### Scenario: Consistent 404 response for missing file\n\n- **GIVEN** any endpoint that reads a file\n- **WHEN** the file does not exist\n- **THEN** the response is HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"File not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n\n#### Scenario: 413 for oversized request body\n\n- **GIVEN** a request body exceeds `MaxBodySize` (32 MiB)\n- **WHEN** the JWT middleware wraps the body with `http.MaxBytesReader`\n- **THEN** the handler receives a read error and responds HTTP 413\n\n### Requirement: Path sanitization reuse\n\nAll file management handlers SHALL use the same `sanitizePath` function from AR-015. The function SHALL be moved to the `files/` subpackage or made accessible to it. All path inputs SHALL be sanitized before any file system operation.\n\n#### Scenario: All endpoints sanitize paths\n\n- **GIVEN** any file management endpoint\n- **WHEN** a request with `path` containing `\"..\"` is received\n- **THEN** `sanitizePath` is called before any file operation\n\n#### Scenario: Workspace jail is enforced across all endpoints\n\n- **GIVEN** a symlink inside the workspace pointing outside\n- **WHEN** any endpoint resolves the symlink path\n- **THEN** the re-verification step detects the escape and returns access denied\n\n### Requirement: Backward compatibility with AR-015 tests\n\nAll existing tests for AR-015 file operations (upload, list, download) SHALL continue to pass after refactoring. Test files SHALL be updated to import from the `files/` subpackage where necessary.\n\n#### Scenario: AR-015 upload tests pass\n\n- **GIVEN** the refactored codebase\n- **WHEN** `go test ./pkg/picod/... -run Upload` is run\n- **THEN** all upload-related tests pass\n\n#### Scenario: AR-015 list tests pass\n\n- **GIVEN** the refactored codebase\n- **WHEN** `go test ./pkg/picod/... -run List` is run\n- **THEN** all list-related tests pass\n\n#### Scenario: AR-015 download tests pass\n\n- **GIVEN** the refactored codebase\n- **WHEN** `go test ./pkg/picod/... -run Download` is run\n- **THEN** all download-related tests pass\n\n#### Scenario: AR-015 sanitize tests pass\n\n- **GIVEN** the refactored codebase\n- **WHEN** `go test ./pkg/picod/... -run Sanitize` is run\n- **THEN** 